s ships and crew, and the dedicated, often obsessive, men and women who embarked on them. Potter discusses the crucial role that Inuit oral accounts, often cited but rarely understood, played in all of these searches, and continue to play to this day, and offers historical and cultural context to the contemporary debates over the significance of Franklin’s achievement. While examination of HMS Erebus will undoubtedly reveal further details of this mystery, Finding Franklin assembles the stories behind the myth and illuminates what is ultimately a remarkable decades-long discovery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFranklin, John 1786-1847xFranklin, John 1786-1847xFranklin, John 1786-1847xErebus (Ship)xErebus (Ship)xErebus (Navire)xShipwrecksxCanada, NorthernxDiscovery and exploration, BritishxShipwrecksxTRAVELxAustralia and OceaniazCanadaxHistoryxGeneralxNaufragesxCanada (Nord)xExpéditions scientifiquesxHistoirexArctiquexNorthwest PassagexDiscovery and explorationxBritishzArctic regionsxDiscovery and explorationxBritishzArctic OceanxNorthwest PassagezArctic RegionsxCanada, Northern. 0aNorthwest Passage--Discovery and exploration--British. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359961140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773599611423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773599611/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles